WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.100 --> 00:00:00.880
All right. Hello, everybody.

2
00:00:01.900 --> 00:00:05.000
Afternoon. Thanks for joining us. Thanks for finding the room.

3
00:00:05.560 --> 00:00:06.980
I was just laughing that

4
00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:11.920
I think two years ago when we had one of the first cachexia sessions at AACR,

5
00:00:12.040 --> 00:00:15.820
we were really deep in the back, and everyone had trouble finding the room.

6
00:00:15.860 --> 00:00:18.120
And so you can see how cachexia is exploding.

7
00:00:18.680 --> 00:00:22.210
We now have a much easier room to find and more people in the audience, so it's

8
00:00:22.280 --> 00:00:23.020
been excellent.

9
00:00:24.420 --> 00:00:27.680
So this is an educational session to talk about the clinical and molecular

10
00:00:27.740 --> 00:00:31.660
phenotyping of cancer cachexia. You may have noticed an earlier

11
00:00:31.720 --> 00:00:34.820
session today which was mostly focused on the preclinical.

12
00:00:35.580 --> 00:00:39.480
So we'll try to gear more towards the clinical, although my talk in the end

13
00:00:39.560 --> 00:00:43.339
will try to straddle back and forth between clinical and preclinical.

14
00:00:44.780 --> 00:00:45.620
Here are my disclosures.

15
00:00:48.060 --> 00:00:51.940
So just to save some of our speakers time, I'll introduce cachexia broadly

16
00:00:52.560 --> 00:00:56.200
in about one minute. So cancer cachexia is a disabling

17
00:00:56.260 --> 00:01:00.120
wasting condition affecting over 80% of patients with advanced

18
00:01:00.180 --> 00:01:04.041
cancer. That translates to somewhere between eight and 10 million patients

19
00:01:04.080 --> 00:01:05.610
with cancer worldwide every year.

20
00:01:06.380 --> 00:01:10.120
And it severely impairs quality of life, limits cancer

21
00:01:10.220 --> 00:01:14.140
treatment and the duration of treatment, and contributes directly to

22
00:01:14.180 --> 00:01:14.760
cancer death.

23
00:01:15.720 --> 00:01:19.580
It's diagnosed clinically as 5% weight loss over six months, or

24
00:01:19.660 --> 00:01:23.630
you can have 2% weight loss if your BMI is already low, less

25
00:01:23.680 --> 00:01:24.160
than 20.

26
00:01:25.320 --> 00:01:27.800
And in humans, we have a poor mechanistic understanding.

27
00:01:27.840 --> 00:01:31.550
There's been numerous failed trials, and currently, there's no approved therapy in

28
00:01:31.600 --> 00:01:32.580
the US or EU.

29
00:01:36.080 --> 00:01:39.460
So just as a brief introduction on today's session,

30
00:01:40.200 --> 00:01:43.640
we'll start with Ed Reznik from Memorial Sloan Kettering, who is really

31
00:01:44.300 --> 00:01:47.840
redefining the field of cachexia and discovering novel features that you'll hear

32
00:01:47.910 --> 00:01:51.380
about using patient data from the electronic medical record.

33
00:01:52.140 --> 00:01:55.630
And then we'll move to Rich Dunn from University of Rochester Medical

34
00:01:55.640 --> 00:01:58.490
Center, who will describe cachexia subtypes.

35
00:01:59.300 --> 00:02:02.860
And then lastly, I'll discuss some translational data that we

36
00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:06.550
have studying the mechanism of cachexia and immunotherapy resistance.

37
00:02:09.039 --> 00:02:11.960
And with that, I will pass the baton to Ed.

38
00:02:19.820 --> 00:02:22.500
All right, well, thank you very much, Marcus, for the invitation to speak.

39
00:02:24.640 --> 00:02:28.500
My name is Ed. I'm a PI at MSK, and I lead

40
00:02:28.560 --> 00:02:32.180
a computational lab that studies tumor metabolism and physiology.

41
00:02:33.320 --> 00:02:36.840
And by way of that, we've sort of recently become interested in the last few years

42
00:02:36.960 --> 00:02:38.000
about cachexia.

43
00:02:39.200 --> 00:02:41.980
So how do I advance?

44
00:02:44.200 --> 00:02:44.920
That arrow.

45
00:02:45.780 --> 00:02:46.240
That arrow?

46
00:02:48.260 --> 00:02:49.300
Hmm.

47
00:02:50.500 --> 00:02:52.540
The directional arrow?

48
00:02:52.600 --> 00:02:53.860
Yeah, the down arrow. Maybe.

49
00:02:59.020 --> 00:02:59.940
Am I missing something?

50
00:03:00.040 --> 00:03:00.180
No.

51
00:03:01.880 --> 00:03:02.500
There maybe. Yeah.

52
00:03:02.670 --> 00:03:08.940
Your

53
00:03:08.980 --> 00:03:10.800
mouse is acting advanced.

54
00:03:11.420 --> 00:03:12.480
Yeah, maybe they'll reset it.

55
00:03:14.360 --> 00:03:15.740
Yeah.

56
00:03:16.290 --> 00:03:19.680
The data that I'm going to show you is so cool that it actually crashed the system.

57
00:03:19.900 --> 00:03:20.900
I apologize for that.

58
00:03:26.980 --> 00:03:27.340
Now yours?

59
00:03:27.400 --> 00:03:28.600
Yeah, sorry. It's fine. Yeah.

60
00:03:30.900 --> 00:03:32.910
Try to click

61
00:03:36.160 --> 00:03:36.850
here.

62
00:03:38.380 --> 00:03:38.760
All right.

63
00:03:39.600 --> 00:03:42.820
So these are my disclosures. I wish they had anything to do with cachexia, but they

64
00:03:42.840 --> 00:03:46.740
don't. And this is an educational session, so I thought I would

65
00:03:47.060 --> 00:03:50.880
try to impart on you some lessons that our group has learned in the

66
00:03:50.920 --> 00:03:54.880
last few years about cachexia. I have to admit, I'm a student myself, so

67
00:03:54.980 --> 00:03:56.800
I really can't say I know much.

68
00:03:58.200 --> 00:04:01.740
But along the way of working on this problem, we've learned a few

69
00:04:01.800 --> 00:04:05.640
valuable things that I think can sort of reorient

70
00:04:05.700 --> 00:04:06.160
how people

71
00:04:07.560 --> 00:04:10.700
study cancer cachexia in human cancer patients.

72
00:04:11.260 --> 00:04:13.560
I didn't want to bury the lead, so I'm just going to tell you what they are.

73
00:04:13.660 --> 00:04:17.149
The first one is that we view cachexia as an ongoing process.

74
00:04:18.060 --> 00:04:21.870
What we've come to realize is that it's important to remember that many patients

75
00:04:21.940 --> 00:04:24.480
just haven't experienced cachexia yet.

76
00:04:24.980 --> 00:04:27.880
And the third lesson, which is probably the most valuable and impactful, is that if

77
00:04:27.900 --> 00:04:31.150
you want to study this in humans, you actually have to look at

78
00:04:31.200 --> 00:04:34.940
them. And as you'll see, that's a privileged thing

79
00:04:35.010 --> 00:04:38.720
that physicians can do easily but computational biologists cannot do

80
00:04:38.760 --> 00:04:42.570
easily. So Marcus mentioned that

81
00:04:42.860 --> 00:04:46.720
while there are many overlapping criteria for cachexia, the sort of

82
00:04:46.800 --> 00:04:50.680
common pattern among them is that you have to have a pre-specified amount

83
00:04:50.720 --> 00:04:54.520
of weight loss, usually 5% of your body weight loss over a six or

84
00:04:54.620 --> 00:04:55.500
12-month period.

85
00:04:56.460 --> 00:05:00.340
And so what our group decided to do was to try to actually implement

86
00:05:00.380 --> 00:05:04.300
that criterion. It's slightly non-trivial to do, but the idea is

87
00:05:04.360 --> 00:05:08.080
that if you have a patient's longitudinal weight trajectory, you can

88
00:05:08.220 --> 00:05:12.200
smooth it out and then look for windows of time when a patient

89
00:05:12.520 --> 00:05:16.140
satisfies that criterion. They actually lose 5% of their body weight over six

90
00:05:16.200 --> 00:05:20.060
months. This seems like a kind of minor math

91
00:05:20.120 --> 00:05:22.890
exercise, but it actually proves to be very useful.

92
00:05:24.260 --> 00:05:27.740
Because what it does is it sort of divides a patient's timeline

93
00:05:27.800 --> 00:05:31.660
into these discrete time-restricted

94
00:05:31.720 --> 00:05:32.480
windows. So

95
00:05:33.740 --> 00:05:34.420
what we learned

96
00:05:35.500 --> 00:05:37.980
is that essentially patients are--

97
00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:42.500
If you discretize their time trajectories into these windows, then when you ask

98
00:05:42.560 --> 00:05:45.600
questions about cachexia, you can sort of anchor them against the windows.

99
00:05:46.180 --> 00:05:49.740
So for example, if you're interested in risk factors for cachexia, you would want

100
00:05:49.760 --> 00:05:52.240
to take measurements before cachexia started.

101
00:05:52.340 --> 00:05:54.900
If you're interested in the phenotype that cachexia imparts on you,

102
00:05:55.800 --> 00:05:57.400
you would want to look within the window.

103
00:05:57.450 --> 00:06:00.720
And if you want to understand the residual effect of cachexia, well, then you have

104
00:06:00.740 --> 00:06:04.516
to look outside of the window.And importantly, for example,

105
00:06:04.716 --> 00:06:07.976
you can anchor other kinds of interesting measurements against these windows.

106
00:06:08.036 --> 00:06:11.996
So if you're interested in therapy, you can actually align therapeutic windows

107
00:06:12.136 --> 00:06:13.996
against our cachexia windows.

108
00:06:14.876 --> 00:06:18.596
So what we did is, using the rich data resource at MSK,

109
00:06:18.956 --> 00:06:22.856
we aligned body weight trajectories in these windows against other kinds of

110
00:06:22.876 --> 00:06:26.616
measurements in the EHR to try to phenotype cancer

111
00:06:26.676 --> 00:06:30.356
patients with cachexia. So the kinds of data that we typically have are

112
00:06:30.416 --> 00:06:32.776
serology, so usually CVCs and CMPs.

113
00:06:33.276 --> 00:06:37.176
We have some data on therapeutic progression, and we have usually

114
00:06:37.236 --> 00:06:38.976
some measure of baseline genomics.

115
00:06:40.196 --> 00:06:43.416
Okay, so where does this get you? I think it gets you quite a lot.

116
00:06:43.676 --> 00:06:43.836
So,

117
00:06:44.996 --> 00:06:48.536
one of the puzzling things in the cachexia field is that some basic

118
00:06:48.596 --> 00:06:52.426
information about prevalence and incidence is not widely available, and

119
00:06:52.476 --> 00:06:56.296
it's not uniformly curated. And so what you can do is actually apply

120
00:06:56.336 --> 00:06:59.316
this criterion and then just start counting arithmetically.

121
00:06:59.936 --> 00:07:03.296
And what you find then is that for every disease, there's actually a nontrivial

122
00:07:03.336 --> 00:07:06.836
burden of weight loss that meets the criterion for cachexia,

123
00:07:07.336 --> 00:07:10.236
even in diseases that are not typically associated with cachexia.

124
00:07:10.316 --> 00:07:13.876
So, for example, in melanoma, something like 30% of patients

125
00:07:13.936 --> 00:07:17.396
experience at least one weight loss episode that meets the criteria for cachexia.

126
00:07:17.996 --> 00:07:21.296
And even if you boost this to 15% weight loss over six months, that would be like

127
00:07:21.336 --> 00:07:25.316
me losing 30 pounds over six months, every disease shows some

128
00:07:25.436 --> 00:07:27.276
patients that experience this phenomenon.

129
00:07:28.416 --> 00:07:31.956
And the important thing to remember, of course, is that this is not necessarily due

130
00:07:31.996 --> 00:07:32.536
to the tumor.

131
00:07:33.976 --> 00:07:35.846
The patients are experiencing therapy.

132
00:07:35.896 --> 00:07:38.226
They're being treated for cancer, and so this is

133
00:07:39.156 --> 00:07:42.316
the convoluted effect of all the things that are happening to a patient.

134
00:07:43.076 --> 00:07:47.056
But what you can see is that diseases like pancreatic cancer, which we know are

135
00:07:47.256 --> 00:07:50.036
commonly associated with cachexia, they come out at the top.

136
00:07:50.516 --> 00:07:53.316
But then other diseases like kidney cancer, where you would just really never

137
00:07:53.356 --> 00:07:56.976
associate with cachexia, they actually have a comparable prevalence

138
00:07:57.496 --> 00:07:58.836
to other GI cancers like

139
00:07:59.816 --> 00:08:00.896
colon adenocarcinoma.

140
00:08:02.096 --> 00:08:06.056
So what you learn if you do this systematically across our data set is that, for

141
00:08:06.096 --> 00:08:08.936
example, patients can experience more than one bout of cachexia.

142
00:08:09.416 --> 00:08:12.596
I think that's not really acknowledged, but it should be intuitive.

143
00:08:13.116 --> 00:08:14.936
There's no reason why they shouldn't be able to do that.

144
00:08:15.356 --> 00:08:18.856
And some patients experience longer periods or bouts of

145
00:08:18.936 --> 00:08:22.156
cachexia than others. Sometimes it's a very focal weight loss event,

146
00:08:22.636 --> 00:08:23.516
sometimes it's not.

147
00:08:25.276 --> 00:08:28.936
And interestingly, if you try and time the

148
00:08:29.116 --> 00:08:32.817
cachexia against interesting landmarks in a patient's care, so for example, a

149
00:08:32.856 --> 00:08:36.456
diagnosis or a death, what you see is that when patients are

150
00:08:36.476 --> 00:08:40.096
approaching the end of their lives, they actually have a pretty uniform rate or

151
00:08:40.216 --> 00:08:44.036
risk of cachexia. It's really a diagnosis that a lot of the variation

152
00:08:44.536 --> 00:08:48.176
comes about. And so actually, that's really what drives the difference between RCC

153
00:08:48.236 --> 00:08:50.826
and colorectal cancer. It's all diagnosis.

154
00:08:52.266 --> 00:08:55.736
So what you can do also is you can anchor, again, interesting

155
00:08:55.756 --> 00:08:57.876
phenotypic measurements against these time windows.

156
00:08:58.496 --> 00:09:02.476
So here I'm showing you on the left a plot of albumin levels, which can be a marker

157
00:09:02.516 --> 00:09:05.336
either of malnutrition or a problem with hepatic synthesis.

158
00:09:05.876 --> 00:09:09.356
And you can see clearly that when you align them against a real patient's body

159
00:09:09.426 --> 00:09:13.116
weight, it's clear that albumin goes down

160
00:09:13.336 --> 00:09:17.016
during periods of weight loss. That should not be surprising, but because we have

161
00:09:17.236 --> 00:09:21.036
60,000 instances of data just like this, we can use

162
00:09:21.096 --> 00:09:24.576
mixed effects models to actually try and hone in on what the

163
00:09:24.616 --> 00:09:27.246
physiologic signature of cachectic weight loss is.

164
00:09:27.416 --> 00:09:30.896
And it has three broad features that I would say

165
00:09:31.176 --> 00:09:34.156
surprisingly don't vary across diseases.

166
00:09:34.576 --> 00:09:38.436
The patients are anemic. They seem to be experiencing malnutrition, at

167
00:09:38.476 --> 00:09:42.056
least from the perspective of albumin, and they have liver dysfunction.

168
00:09:42.096 --> 00:09:43.776
They have elevated liver function tests.

169
00:09:45.556 --> 00:09:49.316
So that's the first lesson, that if you want to do this right, I think you have to

170
00:09:49.356 --> 00:09:53.316
treat cachexia as an ongoing process and just anchor whatever measurements you

171
00:09:53.376 --> 00:09:57.176
make against that. The second lesson, just to put it in a

172
00:09:57.216 --> 00:10:01.125
more principled way, is that we view cachexia as a right-censored event,

173
00:10:01.296 --> 00:10:03.816
something like overall survival or PFS.

174
00:10:04.596 --> 00:10:08.556
And to illustrate why this is important, because we had so much genomics

175
00:10:08.576 --> 00:10:12.136
data right from the get-go, we are trying to associate genomic

176
00:10:12.236 --> 00:10:15.276
features with the incidence of cachexia.

177
00:10:15.996 --> 00:10:18.825
And this is an example of a real plot that our

178
00:10:21.176 --> 00:10:25.026
student, Venise made in 2023 that was very highly powered,

179
00:10:25.996 --> 00:10:29.216
trying to associate genomic features with the risk of cachexia across diseases.

180
00:10:29.616 --> 00:10:33.096
And I'm pointing out that on the y-axis is just the negative log 10 uncorrected P

181
00:10:33.136 --> 00:10:36.696
values. So we have no statistically significant hits even

182
00:10:36.756 --> 00:10:39.976
before a P value correction. There's nothing there in the

183
00:10:40.036 --> 00:10:43.966
data. And part of the reason that there's nothing there is that you may have a

184
00:10:43.996 --> 00:10:47.636
patient that's at very high risk for cachexia, but if they've just arrived at your

185
00:10:47.696 --> 00:10:51.576
clinic, unless they overtly have cachexia already, they just

186
00:10:51.616 --> 00:10:54.286
haven't had any adequate time to really develop cachexia.

187
00:10:54.316 --> 00:10:58.136
They're still at very high risk, and it's just like disease progression or death.

188
00:10:58.596 --> 00:11:01.916
And so what you can do is instead of modeling cachexia as a binary event, you can

189
00:11:01.956 --> 00:11:03.636
model it as a time to event process.

190
00:11:04.096 --> 00:11:06.376
And when you do that, you immediately start seeing signals.

191
00:11:06.536 --> 00:11:10.016
So this is, for example, P53 mutation in one adenocarcinoma.

192
00:11:10.676 --> 00:11:14.516
The signal should be really apparent to you. It's highly significant.

193
00:11:15.116 --> 00:11:18.956
If you do this across diseases, what you find is that there are many genomic

194
00:11:19.456 --> 00:11:22.746
correlates of risk of cachexia, and the clear smoking

195
00:11:22.856 --> 00:11:26.736
gun is P53, which I don't think is really canonically

196
00:11:26.776 --> 00:11:29.276
associated with cachexia in the literature.

197
00:11:29.936 --> 00:11:33.336
If you don't believe me, we actually validated these findings at

198
00:11:33.376 --> 00:11:36.596
Dana-Farber. We also validated them by correcting for various

199
00:11:37.076 --> 00:11:40.476
demographic and clinical factors, including, most importantly, clinical stage.

200
00:11:40.976 --> 00:11:43.316
And we also validated it by looking at dose responses.

201
00:11:43.356 --> 00:11:46.836
So as you up the minimum weight loss that you need to be called

202
00:11:46.856 --> 00:11:49.986
cachectic, the signal that survives is really P53.

203
00:11:50.516 --> 00:11:54.096
So it's clear that P53 in several disease contexts is highly

204
00:11:54.136 --> 00:11:55.676
associated with risk of cachexia.

205
00:11:56.956 --> 00:11:58.486
So all the stuff I've told you so far

206
00:11:59.456 --> 00:12:02.066
is actually in a preprint that's in revision right now.

207
00:12:02.556 --> 00:12:06.516
And the third lesson is totally unpublished, but I think is really

208
00:12:06.556 --> 00:12:10.452
exciting andThe lesson that I

209
00:12:10.472 --> 00:12:13.652
think brought us to that work is that we realized that if we wanted to study

210
00:12:13.692 --> 00:12:17.662
wasting in people, we actually had to look at them And I

211
00:12:17.692 --> 00:12:21.652
mean it literally because I came to learn that there was

212
00:12:21.692 --> 00:12:25.372
a major difference between the physicians and the scientists in our lab, the

213
00:12:25.412 --> 00:12:29.032
PhDs who are studying cachexia, and that the physicians

214
00:12:29.492 --> 00:12:33.392
repeatedly encountered patients and had an intuitive understanding

215
00:12:33.452 --> 00:12:37.212
of how they were actually losing weight and wasting, and in contrast, the

216
00:12:37.252 --> 00:12:41.052
PhD scientists really did not. And so we had to find a way

217
00:12:41.172 --> 00:12:45.152
to actually look at the patients that we were

218
00:12:45.272 --> 00:12:49.192
proposing to study. So we came up with this hypothesis,

219
00:12:49.252 --> 00:12:52.872
admittedly post-hoc, that we could use routinely

220
00:12:52.952 --> 00:12:56.152
ordered CT data to understand how patients' bodies change

221
00:12:56.932 --> 00:12:59.912
during cachexia. And ideally, we could use that

222
00:13:00.132 --> 00:13:03.112
information to define subtypes of cachexia.

223
00:13:03.142 --> 00:13:06.362
And what would distinguish this from other approaches is that

224
00:13:07.152 --> 00:13:10.892
this would be based totally on anatomy rather than molecular features.

225
00:13:11.992 --> 00:13:12.112
So

226
00:13:13.192 --> 00:13:16.552
what's our approach to this? This work is led by Sonia in the lab.

227
00:13:16.592 --> 00:13:20.312
Basically, we look for weight loss episodes that meet the clinical criteria for

228
00:13:20.412 --> 00:13:23.752
cachexia, and then we identify CT scans that flank

229
00:13:24.272 --> 00:13:27.772
the weight loss period, so a CT scan before, a CT scan after.

230
00:13:29.272 --> 00:13:33.262
And then we analyze those CT scans for changes in body composition and

231
00:13:33.292 --> 00:13:33.872
anatomy.

232
00:13:35.012 --> 00:13:38.582
So what does our data set look like? We started with 60,000 patients.

233
00:13:39.132 --> 00:13:42.492
Through some attrition, we landed at about 5,000 patients for where we

234
00:13:42.572 --> 00:13:46.382
have both pre-cachexia and post-cachexia CT scans

235
00:13:46.892 --> 00:13:48.812
heavily dominated by colon and pancreas cancer.

236
00:13:48.872 --> 00:13:51.452
But actually there are some weird diseases in there too, like melanoma.

237
00:13:53.372 --> 00:13:55.032
And what we do is we use a

238
00:13:57.072 --> 00:14:01.032
computational algorithm called OSNIR that automatically analyzes

239
00:14:01.572 --> 00:14:02.472
CT scans

240
00:14:03.432 --> 00:14:07.262
by segmenting those CT scans into interesting body compartments and

241
00:14:07.292 --> 00:14:08.492
then calculating

242
00:14:10.732 --> 00:14:13.032
quantified features of those body compartments.

243
00:14:13.652 --> 00:14:17.552
So what OSNIR specifically does is it navigates to a

244
00:14:17.572 --> 00:14:19.922
predefined spinal level in the axial series.

245
00:14:20.472 --> 00:14:22.892
We use L3, but actually they're all pretty equivalent.

246
00:14:23.712 --> 00:14:27.612
And it automatically segments skeletal muscle, visceral fat, subcutaneous

247
00:14:27.652 --> 00:14:31.392
fat, and then it also segments organs, and it tells us interesting information

248
00:14:31.432 --> 00:14:34.862
about those compartments. So it tells us areas, radiographic

249
00:14:34.862 --> 00:14:35.972
densities, and in the

250
00:14:37.012 --> 00:14:38.982
context of organs, it tells us volumes.

251
00:14:39.552 --> 00:14:43.152
This is an example of a patient pre and post cachexia, and you can see

252
00:14:43.192 --> 00:14:47.092
they're pretty different. This patient loses a ton of fat and

253
00:14:47.152 --> 00:14:48.372
almost no muscle.

254
00:14:49.952 --> 00:14:53.812
So if we do this across our entire trial cohort, we see a few interesting things.

255
00:14:54.432 --> 00:14:54.982
One is that,

256
00:14:56.352 --> 00:15:00.092
not quite unanimously, but pretty uniformly, patients

257
00:15:00.232 --> 00:15:03.892
lose fat and muscle, intramuscular fat,

258
00:15:03.972 --> 00:15:07.552
visceral fat, subcutaneous fat, and skeletal muscle, but organ changes in

259
00:15:07.612 --> 00:15:11.392
volume are more heterogeneous. Sometimes you see organs go up in volume, sometimes

260
00:15:11.412 --> 00:15:12.232
you see them go down.

261
00:15:14.152 --> 00:15:17.492
And so if you give a computational biologist a matrix of data, it's

262
00:15:17.552 --> 00:15:20.032
unsurprising that they would try to cluster it.

263
00:15:20.752 --> 00:15:23.752
So that's what we did. And what we arrived at,

264
00:15:23.972 --> 00:15:27.772
surprisingly, is three pretty clean clusters of data.

265
00:15:28.672 --> 00:15:32.612
And so remember, every one of the columns in this matrix

266
00:15:32.652 --> 00:15:33.282
is a patient,

267
00:15:34.132 --> 00:15:37.812
and all of them are losing weight. They all meet the clinical criteria by weight

268
00:15:37.872 --> 00:15:41.362
loss for cachexia, which is the criterion that, for example, is used in the

269
00:15:41.372 --> 00:15:44.742
penciclib trial. So everybody's losing weight, but they have

270
00:15:44.772 --> 00:15:48.352
these variations in how their anatomy changes.

271
00:15:48.402 --> 00:15:52.352
So what defines these clusters? So type A and type B in our hands

272
00:15:52.912 --> 00:15:55.312
are characterized by profound adipose loss.

273
00:15:55.352 --> 00:15:59.092
They all lose a ton of fat and muscle.

274
00:16:00.172 --> 00:16:03.852
But actually what differentiates them is what happens in the

275
00:16:03.932 --> 00:16:07.892
organs. So in type A, you see progressive increases in spleen

276
00:16:07.912 --> 00:16:11.572
and liver volume. And in type B, you see atrophy of the organs

277
00:16:11.772 --> 00:16:15.672
that's correlated to an increase in radiographic density across all

278
00:16:15.712 --> 00:16:18.052
the organs. It's not restricted to one organ.

279
00:16:18.652 --> 00:16:21.112
So it's as if in type A, the organs are getting bigger.

280
00:16:21.152 --> 00:16:24.292
In type B, they're getting smaller and becoming more radiodense.

281
00:16:25.452 --> 00:16:28.631
This is a prototypical example of a type A cachexia patient.

282
00:16:28.712 --> 00:16:31.172
You can see that their subcutaneous fat goes down a bunch.

283
00:16:31.852 --> 00:16:34.772
I don't know if you can see my mouse, but if you actually look at this orange

284
00:16:34.832 --> 00:16:36.112
region over here, this is the spleen.

285
00:16:36.152 --> 00:16:39.882
And if you orient yourself against the rib, it's clear that the spleen is getting

286
00:16:39.932 --> 00:16:43.872
much bigger post cachexia, despite the fact that they're losing a ton of

287
00:16:43.912 --> 00:16:44.172
weight.

288
00:16:46.072 --> 00:16:49.972
So if you try and pin these against overall outcomes, for example, correlating

289
00:16:50.032 --> 00:16:53.852
against survival at the end of the cachectic episode, what you find

290
00:16:53.912 --> 00:16:57.752
is that the type A subtype with progressive increases in spleen and liver volume

291
00:16:57.792 --> 00:17:01.432
does the worst almost uniformly across diseases, although not

292
00:17:01.492 --> 00:17:02.492
completely uniformly.

293
00:17:03.872 --> 00:17:07.373
And so we have this sort of framework now for

294
00:17:07.452 --> 00:17:09.932
categorizing the subtypes.

295
00:17:11.272 --> 00:17:12.432
But we don't really know

296
00:17:14.172 --> 00:17:16.732
what is going on, what might be the etiology of them.

297
00:17:17.152 --> 00:17:20.652
So the way that we approach this is to actually, again, repurpose our blood lab

298
00:17:20.672 --> 00:17:24.113
data. Here I'm showing you a plot of the neutrophil to lymphocyte ratio, which is

299
00:17:24.133 --> 00:17:26.032
sort of a marker of systemic inflammation.

300
00:17:26.652 --> 00:17:28.712
And I'm stratifying patients by subtype and

301
00:17:29.572 --> 00:17:32.492
sort of tracking their NLR across the weight loss episode.

302
00:17:33.032 --> 00:17:36.812
So what you find is that actually the type A patients, actually all the patients

303
00:17:36.872 --> 00:17:38.832
start at a relatively similar NLR.

304
00:17:39.232 --> 00:17:42.192
But by the end of the episode, the type A patients have

305
00:17:42.692 --> 00:17:46.312
massively elevated NLR as if they're systemically inflamed.

306
00:17:46.932 --> 00:17:50.492
At the same time, actually, the type A patients start with the highest albumin, but

307
00:17:50.512 --> 00:17:54.062
by the end of cachexia, they have the lowest albumin, and they're the only ones

308
00:17:54.072 --> 00:17:58.052
that have albumin that actually falls below the critical threshold for calling

309
00:17:58.112 --> 00:18:01.916
hypoalbuminemia.Finally, if you look in liver function

310
00:18:01.996 --> 00:18:05.576
tests, it's clear that there's something messed up about the type A

311
00:18:05.616 --> 00:18:07.236
cachexia patients in their liver.

312
00:18:08.216 --> 00:18:12.096
Okay, so from this, we basically arrived at a simple hypothesis, which

313
00:18:12.136 --> 00:18:15.756
is that we think that the type A patients exhibit markers

314
00:18:15.876 --> 00:18:19.106
of systemic inflammation that may not be so evident in the other

315
00:18:19.256 --> 00:18:23.096
subtypes of cachectic patients. How would we

316
00:18:23.156 --> 00:18:23.696
test that?

317
00:18:24.656 --> 00:18:28.556
One non-trivial implication of that is that if you could somehow measure organs,

318
00:18:29.976 --> 00:18:33.826
phenotype organs in the body, not just using radiographic information, but using

319
00:18:33.856 --> 00:18:37.696
molecular measurements, you would see evidence of inflammation in the organs.

320
00:18:38.276 --> 00:18:41.136
So we were very lucky because there was actually a group doing this at our

321
00:18:41.156 --> 00:18:44.856
institution. This is a collaborative effort between David Lydon,

322
00:18:45.576 --> 00:18:48.246
Bill Jarnagin, who's the surgeon, and Robert Schwartz, who's the

323
00:18:48.856 --> 00:18:52.376
hepatologist, where for about 40 patients who were

324
00:18:52.416 --> 00:18:55.716
receiving pancreatectomies, during the surgical

325
00:18:55.756 --> 00:18:59.675
procedure, a piece of the uninvolved non-metastatic liver

326
00:18:59.756 --> 00:19:03.576
was profiled. They took a chunk and they submitted it for RNA-Seq.

327
00:19:04.276 --> 00:19:07.876
And if you actually get the CT scans for these patients, what you see is that

328
00:19:07.996 --> 00:19:11.256
they're roughly evenly divided between type A, type B, and type C

329
00:19:11.266 --> 00:19:15.166
cachexia. And when you compare the gene expression programs in

330
00:19:15.196 --> 00:19:17.536
the uninvolved liver prior to weight loss

331
00:19:18.576 --> 00:19:22.516
between type A and type C, what you see is that type A livers seem

332
00:19:22.576 --> 00:19:25.496
to already exhibit the signature of

333
00:19:25.876 --> 00:19:28.476
elevated downstream inflammatory signaling.

334
00:19:30.216 --> 00:19:34.076
So what you would really like to know is if the signal is coming from

335
00:19:34.136 --> 00:19:38.116
the tumor or from somewhere else, what the extent of systemic involvement

336
00:19:38.136 --> 00:19:38.416
is.

337
00:19:39.716 --> 00:19:43.576
So we tried to do this, and it's a difficult

338
00:19:43.716 --> 00:19:47.616
ask. And the reason is that if you want to profile

339
00:19:48.656 --> 00:19:52.296
risk factors for cachexia, you need tissue, again, that is

340
00:19:52.316 --> 00:19:54.356
collected prior to the onset of weight loss.

341
00:19:54.416 --> 00:19:58.096
So somehow you need the surgery to happen or the biopsy to happen

342
00:19:58.556 --> 00:20:01.716
before weight loss, and now you're doing this in a retrospective cohort with all

343
00:20:01.776 --> 00:20:04.996
kinds of other attrition. It's not so easy to pull off.

344
00:20:05.096 --> 00:20:08.436
So through a lot of email wrangling, we identified a cohort like this.

345
00:20:08.516 --> 00:20:12.196
This is the MST Spectrum cohort, which longitudinally followed

346
00:20:12.676 --> 00:20:16.476
about 100 high-grade serous ovarian cancer patients and profiled them

347
00:20:16.536 --> 00:20:19.396
using single-cell RNA-Seq and other data modalities.

348
00:20:19.416 --> 00:20:22.646
And again, high-grade serous is not a disease that is ever associated with

349
00:20:22.676 --> 00:20:26.636
cachexia. But what we find is that for 13 patients where we

350
00:20:26.696 --> 00:20:28.276
had single cell,

351
00:20:29.136 --> 00:20:33.016
we are able again to stratify them into type A, type B, and type C

352
00:20:33.436 --> 00:20:36.836
patients. Sometimes these patients had multiple samples collected.

353
00:20:37.256 --> 00:20:41.036
And what you see, you would anticipate that actually inflammatory signaling is

354
00:20:41.176 --> 00:20:45.116
localized to the type A patients. That's not what we see in our hands.

355
00:20:45.236 --> 00:20:47.236
In fact, what we see is that in the tumor cells,

356
00:20:48.056 --> 00:20:51.096
inflammatory signaling is only elevated in type B patients.

357
00:20:51.156 --> 00:20:53.836
Those are the ones that are experiencing organ atrophy.

358
00:20:54.416 --> 00:20:58.196
But actually, if you look outside of the tumor compartment into the myeloid

359
00:20:58.216 --> 00:21:00.716
compartment, that's where we see

360
00:21:01.176 --> 00:21:04.776
elevated interferon or downstream

361
00:21:05.056 --> 00:21:08.376
interferon-stimulated gene signatures.

362
00:21:08.406 --> 00:21:12.396
So I would say we haven't really pinned it down, and my suspicion is that if we

363
00:21:12.436 --> 00:21:14.816
look in other diseases, we'll see different patterns.

364
00:21:14.876 --> 00:21:18.336
I don't really anticipate that we'll see this over and over again, but the data

365
00:21:18.376 --> 00:21:21.976
will tell. So okay. I want to leave you with a few parting

366
00:21:22.056 --> 00:21:25.996
thoughts. This is not a summary of my talk,

367
00:21:26.116 --> 00:21:29.836
but I think that right now the time is ripe for a

368
00:21:29.956 --> 00:21:33.736
new kind of science organized around cachexia that

369
00:21:33.776 --> 00:21:37.756
brings the precision medicine paradigm to bear on studying

370
00:21:38.456 --> 00:21:39.116
physiologic

371
00:21:40.256 --> 00:21:44.016
paraneoplasia like cachexia. And I think the key challenge, which many of

372
00:21:44.076 --> 00:21:45.236
us are already aware of,

373
00:21:46.276 --> 00:21:49.196
is that if you're going to identify subtypes, you actually need to identify the

374
00:21:49.236 --> 00:21:51.116
molecular targets that you could intervene on

375
00:21:51.376 --> 00:21:55.326
to address

376
00:21:55.376 --> 00:21:59.276
those subtypes. And the final thought I want to leave you with is that, in my

377
00:21:59.336 --> 00:22:03.216
view, cachexia is really a grand challenge, not just for

378
00:22:03.576 --> 00:22:06.736
cancer biology, but specifically for computational biology.

379
00:22:07.596 --> 00:22:11.156
This is a setting where you cannot just carry out fancy

380
00:22:11.196 --> 00:22:14.916
molecular measurements and make heat maps in order to make real advances.

381
00:22:14.956 --> 00:22:18.776
The problem is more complicated than that because cachexia is inherently

382
00:22:18.835 --> 00:22:22.236
behavioral, it's physiologic, and it has molecular underpinnings.

383
00:22:22.416 --> 00:22:26.256
And so you need strong computational biologists and

384
00:22:26.356 --> 00:22:28.476
thinkers in order to make progress.

385
00:22:28.936 --> 00:22:29.256
And so

386
00:22:30.236 --> 00:22:34.136
I leave this sort of as an open call for computational biologists who

387
00:22:34.236 --> 00:22:38.136
want to work on an actually hard problem to come into

388
00:22:38.176 --> 00:22:38.696
our field.

389
00:22:39.696 --> 00:22:42.436
So with that, I'll just thank the people who did this and the funding agencies.

390
00:22:42.816 --> 00:22:46.416
And importantly, I left some people out on this slide, especially David

391
00:22:46.436 --> 00:22:46.876
Lydon,

392
00:22:47.716 --> 00:22:51.416
Bill Jarnagin, and Robert Schwartz, and I'll take any questions. Thank you.

393
00:22:56.196 --> 00:22:57.656
Thanks, Ed.

394
00:22:58.976 --> 00:23:02.056
Thanks, Ed. Very inspiring there at the end. We'll open the floor for questions.

395
00:23:02.196 --> 00:23:05.676
Yeah, that was very

396
00:23:05.696 --> 00:23:06.216
inspiring.

397
00:23:07.576 --> 00:23:11.536
Quick question. Did you look at other disease types that develop cachexia to

398
00:23:11.616 --> 00:23:15.416
see if you see these three subtypes in those, like after MI

399
00:23:15.516 --> 00:23:17.016
or COPD? Oh.

400
00:23:18.396 --> 00:23:22.136
So I work at a referral institution for cancer patients.

401
00:23:22.916 --> 00:23:24.936
I guess we haven't really thought about

402
00:23:27.016 --> 00:23:30.156
cachexia associated with MI or burns or something.

403
00:23:30.196 --> 00:23:33.806
We could do it, although it would be hard at our

404
00:23:33.836 --> 00:23:35.156
institution just because

405
00:23:36.496 --> 00:23:39.396
I don't know how prevalent those- Well, you have the models.

406
00:23:39.496 --> 00:23:43.266
You just need a clinical partner to get you that information.

407
00:23:43.316 --> 00:23:47.116
But to do it at scale is hard. To do it at scale, I think is really hard.

408
00:23:47.456 --> 00:23:51.216
Yeah. Well, you have big expectations with 50,000 patients.

409
00:23:52.316 --> 00:23:53.636
Yeah. Just saying, that's-

410
00:23:54.456 --> 00:23:55.796
Yeah ... very rare. Yeah.

411
00:23:57.636 --> 00:24:01.336
And so with that, my next comment will probably bounce off the wall, but we have

412
00:24:02.016 --> 00:24:05.756
1,500 lung cancer patients that have resectable disease that we

413
00:24:05.816 --> 00:24:08.316
have longitudinal CTs on

414
00:24:09.156 --> 00:24:10.516
blood RNA-Seq,

415
00:24:11.596 --> 00:24:14.596
if you want to collaborate. Yeah. I'll come sit right next to you after I'm done.

416
00:24:14.656 --> 00:24:14.836
Okay.

417
00:24:15.876 --> 00:24:16.056
Yeah.

418
00:24:20.400 --> 00:24:24.320
Very interesting talk. A couple observations in

419
00:24:24.420 --> 00:24:25.700
PDAC patients,

420
00:24:26.980 --> 00:24:30.720
both rodent and human. As you're probably

421
00:24:30.780 --> 00:24:34.660
aware with tumor burden in mice, you get splenomegalia

422
00:24:35.840 --> 00:24:39.640
And we were blessed with getting about 60 spleens

423
00:24:39.740 --> 00:24:41.090
from PDAC patients,

424
00:24:41.900 --> 00:24:45.860
and most of them had splenomegalia,

425
00:24:46.460 --> 00:24:50.440
and there's quite an increase in myelohiperplasia, which is

426
00:24:50.480 --> 00:24:53.500
the same thing you see in mice. So I'm

427
00:24:54.060 --> 00:24:57.570
guessing a lot of what you're seeing in the splenomegaly and

428
00:24:57.640 --> 00:25:01.440
probably in the liver is myeloplasia,

429
00:25:02.700 --> 00:25:06.180
extramedullary myeloplasia with myeloid cells.

430
00:25:07.500 --> 00:25:07.560
So-

431
00:25:07.620 --> 00:25:11.120
Certainly, you can get two, three fingers of splenomegaly in some of these

432
00:25:11.220 --> 00:25:11.700
patients.

433
00:25:12.740 --> 00:25:16.549
Yeah. I think at least for the liver observation,

434
00:25:17.220 --> 00:25:20.780
our thinking was that it was steatosis because these patients are just losing a ton

435
00:25:20.800 --> 00:25:22.780
of fat and the liver needs to handle it.

436
00:25:23.900 --> 00:25:27.640
And my understanding is that in other settings, when you lose fat or weight

437
00:25:27.680 --> 00:25:30.160
really quickly, you often develop steatotic liver.

438
00:25:30.900 --> 00:25:33.880
And for the splenomegaly, I'm less sure.

439
00:25:34.500 --> 00:25:36.940
But it tracks with NOR, right? So-

440
00:25:37.260 --> 00:25:37.810
Right. Yeah

441
00:25:37.880 --> 00:25:38.100
Yeah.

442
00:25:39.400 --> 00:25:42.540
So it's probably consistent with some splenomegaly.

443
00:25:42.660 --> 00:25:42.840
Yeah.

444
00:25:46.180 --> 00:25:49.680
Hi. Very interesting talk. I was wondering,

445
00:25:50.460 --> 00:25:53.520
so as the patients receive various forms of therapy,

446
00:25:54.360 --> 00:25:56.500
a lot of them are highly inflammatory.

447
00:25:56.560 --> 00:26:00.060
So I was wondering, do you see, for instance, specifically

448
00:26:00.780 --> 00:26:04.590
chemotherapy and radiation therapy, could they be driving factors for cachexia,

449
00:26:05.020 --> 00:26:07.600
or is it the disease itself that's like that?

450
00:26:07.640 --> 00:26:11.560
And if not, do you see the therapy being a factor in terms

451
00:26:11.600 --> 00:26:12.880
of augmenting cachexia?

452
00:26:13.540 --> 00:26:16.160
Yeah, it's a really important question.

453
00:26:16.220 --> 00:26:19.500
I think it's one of the central questions in our group.

454
00:26:20.180 --> 00:26:23.040
I don't think we have a good framework for...

455
00:26:23.300 --> 00:26:26.920
It's actually my student's PhD thesis or some aspect of it.

456
00:26:27.400 --> 00:26:31.170
I don't think we have a good framework for teasing apart the role of

457
00:26:31.260 --> 00:26:34.840
therapy, and I think, and it has to do with a lot of reasons.

458
00:26:35.520 --> 00:26:35.920
But

459
00:26:38.800 --> 00:26:41.860
it is just very difficult in a causal framework,

460
00:26:42.960 --> 00:26:44.660
I guess, to ascribe

461
00:26:46.220 --> 00:26:49.160
the weight loss or a change in body composition to therapy or not.

462
00:26:49.460 --> 00:26:52.740
I think there are settings where you can do it, like in a clinical trial-

463
00:26:53.240 --> 00:26:53.350
Mm-hmm

464
00:26:53.350 --> 00:26:57.080
... but we don't know. And I think it's sort of this pervasive question in the

465
00:26:57.140 --> 00:27:00.600
field, which is: What does therapy do to

466
00:27:00.640 --> 00:27:04.070
patients? And it's clear that the physicians know something

467
00:27:04.120 --> 00:27:07.760
intuitively about it because I always get this question,

468
00:27:08.160 --> 00:27:11.890
and it seems as if what they're trying to tell me is that we know that

469
00:27:11.900 --> 00:27:15.600
therapy is inducing weight loss through side effects or toxicities in our

470
00:27:15.680 --> 00:27:19.320
patients. But what we're having trouble with is building a

471
00:27:19.400 --> 00:27:23.260
framework where we understand whether weight loss is

472
00:27:23.320 --> 00:27:26.600
a side effect or a natural outcome of the tumor.

473
00:27:26.680 --> 00:27:28.180
I don't know that we have a good way of

474
00:27:29.100 --> 00:27:30.580
discriminating between the two yet.

475
00:27:30.840 --> 00:27:34.780
I see. Have you been able to look at patients with the same tumor

476
00:27:34.800 --> 00:27:36.980
type that have received different therapies to see how the-

477
00:27:37.040 --> 00:27:37.270
Yeah

478
00:27:37.340 --> 00:27:38.170
... cachexia trajectory has gone?

479
00:27:38.660 --> 00:27:40.500
Yeah. That's what we're trying to do.

480
00:27:42.340 --> 00:27:44.720
You can talk to Jamie, who's in the purple shirt right there.

481
00:27:45.400 --> 00:27:48.180
He doesn't have all the answers, but he thinks about it a lot. Yeah.

482
00:27:48.580 --> 00:27:48.860
Thank you.

483
00:27:49.160 --> 00:27:49.340
Yeah.

484
00:27:51.920 --> 00:27:53.780
Hi, I'm Matthias from Ohio State University.

485
00:27:54.700 --> 00:27:56.980
Great talk. Thank you so much for that. Very inspiring.

486
00:27:57.380 --> 00:28:01.360
I was wondering if your group was able to discern patients, for example,

