902
00:50:56.388 --> 00:50:59.108
So as we've already talked about a few times,

903
00:51:00.228 --> 00:51:03.848
it's a multi-organ systemic disease of cachexia,

904
00:51:04.648 --> 00:51:08.538
which likely originates from the tumor or some component of

905
00:51:08.568 --> 00:51:12.448
the tumor microenvironment, including the stroma, the immune

906
00:51:12.528 --> 00:51:16.268
infiltrates, and of course, factors that are made by the tumor and then

907
00:51:16.308 --> 00:51:19.628
ultimately are secreted and can impact many organs,

908
00:51:20.328 --> 00:51:24.188
including the atrophy programs in the muscle and adipose tissue, as

909
00:51:24.228 --> 00:51:26.948
well as reprogramming in the liver and changes in the immune system.

910
00:51:29.828 --> 00:51:33.728
This is data from Ed's cohort, specifically looking at the lung cancer

911
00:51:33.748 --> 00:51:37.568
population. As you can see, cachexia is extremely common in this

912
00:51:37.588 --> 00:51:39.528
population and also very hazardous.

913
00:51:40.228 --> 00:51:41.368
After a bout of cachexia,

914
00:51:42.168 --> 00:51:44.688
the overall survival probability is dramatically reduced

915
00:51:46.308 --> 00:51:48.428
in comparison to patients that don't have cachexia yet.

916
00:51:51.548 --> 00:51:55.248
Part of that poor survival is due to poor

917
00:51:55.288 --> 00:51:59.088
responses to therapy. And one example of this that has come up multiple

918
00:51:59.148 --> 00:52:02.428
times now in the literature is that people with

919
00:52:02.468 --> 00:52:06.348
cachexia have a poor response to immune

920
00:52:06.428 --> 00:52:10.368
checkpoint inhibitor therapy. And here are some examples of that data

921
00:52:10.408 --> 00:52:14.328
over four different publications of modest sample

922
00:52:14.408 --> 00:52:18.248
size. And you can see that in each case, individuals with cachexia

923
00:52:18.268 --> 00:52:21.748
have much shorter progression-free survival than those without

924
00:52:21.788 --> 00:52:22.268
cachexia.

925
00:52:25.588 --> 00:52:27.948
So we decided to take a look at this in a

926
00:52:28.748 --> 00:52:32.228
small cohort that we have at NYU. These are patients with

927
00:52:32.348 --> 00:52:35.848
advanced lung adenocarcinoma receiving immune checkpoint inhibitor

928
00:52:35.928 --> 00:52:39.448
therapy, and they've been nicely phenotyped and tracked over

929
00:52:39.548 --> 00:52:43.228
time, and there were serial body weights available on our electronic medical

930
00:52:43.308 --> 00:52:47.188
record, such that we could define patients as having cachexia

931
00:52:47.208 --> 00:52:51.088
or not. And then we can center ourselves around the start of the immune

932
00:52:51.148 --> 00:52:54.968
checkpoint inhibitor therapy and come up with a pre-time

933
00:52:55.008 --> 00:52:58.088
point and a post-time point, very much inspired by Ed's

934
00:52:58.108 --> 00:52:59.768
work.

935
00:53:00.848 --> 00:53:04.348
And we found four phenotypes when we did this analysis.

936
00:53:05.308 --> 00:53:09.248
There were patients that we call non-cachectic, where they did not have any weight

937
00:53:09.308 --> 00:53:13.188
loss preceding the immune checkpoint inhibitor therapy, and they also did not have

938
00:53:13.208 --> 00:53:16.008
any change in their body weight after the initiation of therapy.

939
00:53:17.288 --> 00:53:21.268
There was also a group we refer to as cachexia or cachexia continued,

940
00:53:21.308 --> 00:53:25.028
which is they developed cachexia or weight loss before the

941
00:53:25.088 --> 00:53:29.028
onset of immunotherapy, and then the immune therapy didn't modulate that

942
00:53:29.068 --> 00:53:31.368
at all. They just continued to lose weight over

943
00:53:31.488 --> 00:53:35.438
time. We then have a group which is

944
00:53:35.448 --> 00:53:39.128
referred to as cachexia started with treatment, also referred to as a

945
00:53:39.228 --> 00:53:40.548
treatment adverse event,

946
00:53:41.348 --> 00:53:45.208
or it could be considered that, where the body weight was relatively

947
00:53:45.268 --> 00:53:49.028
flat leading up to the onset of immune checkpoint inhibitor therapy, and

948
00:53:49.108 --> 00:53:53.028
then there was a very dramatic reduction in body weight after the onset of

949
00:53:53.048 --> 00:53:57.008
treatment. And then lastly, this is the most ideal case in terms of the

950
00:53:57.028 --> 00:54:00.728
patient outcomes, which is patients had cachexia

951
00:54:00.748 --> 00:54:04.538
before the onset of immune checkpoint inhibitor therapy, and that was reversed by

952
00:54:04.568 --> 00:54:05.008
the therapy.

953
00:54:07.508 --> 00:54:10.328
So these changes patterns in body weight led us to

954
00:54:11.148 --> 00:54:15.138
consider and hypothesize what could be driving the underlying etiology

955
00:54:15.168 --> 00:54:18.828
of these patterns. And so we looked at some clinical

956
00:54:18.968 --> 00:54:22.868
demographic and tumor characteristics of these patients, and we

957
00:54:22.908 --> 00:54:24.268
noticed a few interesting

958
00:54:25.268 --> 00:54:29.192
associationsThe first was, let me

959
00:54:29.212 --> 00:54:30.532
see if I can highlight here.

960
00:54:31.552 --> 00:54:35.492
There was very similar demographics in terms of age,

961
00:54:35.572 --> 00:54:36.892
sex, race,

962
00:54:37.752 --> 00:54:38.652
and BMI.

963
00:54:39.672 --> 00:54:43.292
The things that were different here, I highlight, which is PD-L1

964
00:54:43.392 --> 00:54:47.232
high tumors. So those tended to be enriched in patients that had their

965
00:54:47.252 --> 00:54:50.892
cachexia reversed or had the onset of

966
00:54:50.902 --> 00:54:54.872
wasting at the induction of treatment, suggesting

967
00:54:54.892 --> 00:54:58.532
that having high PD-L1 expression leads to a

968
00:54:58.632 --> 00:55:01.972
robust systemic effect both in a positive and negative way.

969
00:55:03.512 --> 00:55:07.432
We also had resist criteria that was done to evaluate the tumor responses,

970
00:55:07.472 --> 00:55:11.272
and you see that those that had a partial response were all in

971
00:55:11.332 --> 00:55:12.982
the cachexia reversed category,

972
00:55:13.832 --> 00:55:16.052
which is, I think, intuitive and what we would expect.

973
00:55:17.192 --> 00:55:20.712
Those that had progressive disease were enriched in the

974
00:55:20.732 --> 00:55:22.032
cachexia continued group.

975
00:55:23.292 --> 00:55:26.992
And those that there were a higher proportion of patients that were

976
00:55:27.012 --> 00:55:30.592
deceased at two years or before two years, they were also

977
00:55:30.632 --> 00:55:34.152
enriched in the cachexia continued. So I think some of this is sort of intuitive.

978
00:55:34.232 --> 00:55:37.882
If the cachexia is continuing, it's likely that the tumor is not

979
00:55:37.892 --> 00:55:41.512
responding, and we were able to show that in the data here.

980
00:55:43.512 --> 00:55:46.942
And this data suggests that the cachexia trajectory is at least

981
00:55:46.992 --> 00:55:50.292
associated with the immune checkpoint inhibitor response and even may predict that

982
00:55:50.312 --> 00:55:51.332
response.

983
00:55:53.032 --> 00:55:55.772
So there are many common features if you look across the

984
00:55:55.792 --> 00:55:59.672
literature that are shared with the

985
00:55:59.692 --> 00:56:03.412
cachectic process and resistance to immune checkpoint inhibitor, and I'm

986
00:56:03.452 --> 00:56:06.972
listing some of those here. Many of them include pro-inflammatory

987
00:56:07.032 --> 00:56:10.002
cytokines that are released from the tumor microenvironment.

988
00:56:10.672 --> 00:56:14.262
And some of these, like the IL-6/STAT3 pathway, have been associated with

989
00:56:14.292 --> 00:56:17.872
both muscle wasting and also these

990
00:56:18.212 --> 00:56:21.232
myeloid suppressing cells in the tumor microenvironment.

991
00:56:22.292 --> 00:56:25.892
And also lipids like prostaglandins, specifically

992
00:56:25.912 --> 00:56:29.732
prostaglandin E2, that have been implicated in reducing appetite

993
00:56:30.612 --> 00:56:33.852
in different sickness conditions and also in T cell suppression.

994
00:56:35.972 --> 00:56:39.812
So this begged the question, is cachexia inherently linked to

995
00:56:39.852 --> 00:56:42.812
changes in tumor microenvironment that then predict the response to immune

996
00:56:42.852 --> 00:56:46.802
checkpoint inhibitor therapy? And so we turn to preclinical models

997
00:56:46.812 --> 00:56:49.542
in order to try to gain some insight into this.

998
00:56:50.722 --> 00:56:53.211
So this is our favorite preclinical model in the lab.

999
00:56:53.252 --> 00:56:56.432
It's a model of lung cancer that has a KRAS

1000
00:56:56.892 --> 00:57:00.872
activating mutation, and also it loses a tumor suppressor, SDK11,

1001
00:57:00.932 --> 00:57:04.542
also called LKB1, and we refer to these mice as KL mice.

1002
00:57:04.592 --> 00:57:08.392
And over the years, we have profiled these mice and tried to intervene on

1003
00:57:08.412 --> 00:57:12.012
cachexia. And one notable feature of this animal model

1004
00:57:12.512 --> 00:57:15.072
is that many of the mice develop cachexia.

1005
00:57:15.112 --> 00:57:18.772
However, there is this non-cachectic group that are

1006
00:57:19.672 --> 00:57:22.961
littermates of these animals and develop similar tumor burden but don't lose

1007
00:57:23.032 --> 00:57:26.442
weight, and we've been able to compare the mice that lose weight to the mice that

1008
00:57:26.472 --> 00:57:27.212
don't lose weight.

1009
00:57:28.912 --> 00:57:31.292
And this is what one of these typical cohorts look like.

1010
00:57:31.932 --> 00:57:35.912
You induce the animal model at zero time, and then you watch them over time,

1011
00:57:35.972 --> 00:57:39.732
measuring body weight serially, and you can see that the majority will lose

1012
00:57:39.792 --> 00:57:43.532
weight, ultimately reaching upwards of 20% weight loss, whereas the

1013
00:57:43.552 --> 00:57:47.332
non-cachectic animals don't have any weight loss, yet they

1014
00:57:47.342 --> 00:57:50.952
develop ample amounts of tumor. And those that develop weight loss

1015
00:57:51.072 --> 00:57:55.022
lose skeletal muscle and adipose tissue and have many other

1016
00:57:55.032 --> 00:57:57.772
features consistent with human cachexia, especially with lung cancer.

1017
00:58:00.212 --> 00:58:03.752
It's known in the field that this KL model also has very poor

1018
00:58:03.792 --> 00:58:07.232
responses to immune checkpoint inhibitor therapy, and this has been shown now for

1019
00:58:07.292 --> 00:58:08.032
over 10 years.

1020
00:58:09.152 --> 00:58:12.172
Treatment with different interventions.

1021
00:58:12.192 --> 00:58:14.552
Here, I'm showing you examples of anti-PD-L1.

1022
00:58:15.272 --> 00:58:19.092
You can see that the change in tumor compared to untreated mice,

1023
00:58:19.412 --> 00:58:23.202
if you look at the anti-PD-L1 antibody two weeks after treatment, you have

1024
00:58:23.252 --> 00:58:25.312
basically the same amount of tumor burden.

1025
00:58:26.012 --> 00:58:29.162
And if you look at survival curves, you really don't have any difference between

1026
00:58:29.192 --> 00:58:33.092
the black line and this light blue line in terms of overall survival

1027
00:58:33.132 --> 00:58:34.512
after initiation of therapy.

1028
00:58:37.512 --> 00:58:41.152
So to gain some insights on what could be driving this, we've looked

1029
00:58:41.512 --> 00:58:45.492
deeply into the tumors of mice with and without cachexia, and we've done

1030
00:58:45.872 --> 00:58:49.232
cytokine profiling in the tumor and also the serum.

1031
00:58:49.252 --> 00:58:52.712
And we've identified many IL-6 family members that are

1032
00:58:52.752 --> 00:58:55.792
uniquely enriched in the animals with cachexia.

1033
00:58:56.702 --> 00:59:00.672
And we've also looked at the immune cells that are present and

1034
00:59:00.752 --> 00:59:03.512
could be driving the production of these cytokines.

1035
00:59:03.952 --> 00:59:07.792
And when we do a single cell, there's these two different myeloid

1036
00:59:07.832 --> 00:59:11.332
populations that are uniquely enriched in the cachectic animals.

1037
00:59:11.792 --> 00:59:15.192
One of them is this arginase positive macrophage, and one is a

1038
00:59:15.432 --> 00:59:18.852
neutrophil that happens to express high degrees of prostaglandin

1039
00:59:19.132 --> 00:59:20.632
synthesis machinery.

1040
00:59:21.612 --> 00:59:25.532
And if you look at our RNA sequencing, you see higher markers

1041
00:59:25.572 --> 00:59:27.392
of immune exhaustion markers

1042
00:59:28.192 --> 00:59:29.192
in the cachectic mice.

1043
00:59:32.612 --> 00:59:36.542
Here's just an example of some of the gene expression from the neutrophils that

1044
00:59:36.572 --> 00:59:40.552
are enriched in the cachectic animals, and I'm showing you one example

1045
00:59:40.612 --> 00:59:43.812
of this prostaglandin synthesis machinery, which is a gene called

1046
00:59:43.852 --> 00:59:47.332
PTGS2, also referred to as COX-2, which is very important for

1047
00:59:47.352 --> 00:59:48.472
prostaglandin production.

1048
00:59:49.332 --> 00:59:52.672
And they are uniquely enriched in the neutrophils.

1049
00:59:52.712 --> 00:59:55.012
They also can be found in the tumor cells themselves.

1050
00:59:55.592 --> 00:59:59.542
And if you go in the tumors and you measure prostaglandin E2, you see that it's

1051
00:59:59.572 --> 01:00:01.872
significantly higher in the cachectic mice.

1052
01:00:05.812 --> 01:00:09.752
If you go back to our human data set, and this data set is

1053
01:00:09.972 --> 01:00:13.732
nice because a pulmonologist was helping us collect the data, and he

1054
01:00:13.772 --> 01:00:17.452
collected bronchoalveolar lavage fluid from the region

1055
01:00:17.512 --> 01:00:18.332
outside the tumor.

1056
01:00:19.152 --> 01:00:22.632
And we can sample that fluid, and we can do

1057
01:00:23.052 --> 01:00:26.972
RNA sequencing on the cells from that fluid, and we can also do measurements

1058
01:00:27.032 --> 01:00:28.812
like prostaglandin E2 from that fluid.

1059
01:00:29.342 --> 01:00:32.552
And if you segregate patients with and without cachexia, you see that the patients

1060
01:00:32.612 --> 01:00:36.252
with cachexia also have high levels of prostaglandin E2 in the

1061
01:00:36.272 --> 01:00:40.132
bronchoalveolar lavage fluid. And if you do sequencing on the tumor

1062
01:00:40.152 --> 01:00:43.312
cells from that fluid, you see that they are enriched in prostaglandin

1063
01:00:43.332 --> 01:00:47.622
signaling.So

1064
01:00:47.662 --> 01:00:51.122
in order to test the contribution of PGE2 to

1065
01:00:51.162 --> 01:00:54.462
cachexia, we partnered with Thalise

1066
01:00:54.602 --> 01:00:55.462
Papagiannakopoulos,

1067
01:00:56.362 --> 01:00:57.742
who's here at AACR.

1068
01:00:58.582 --> 01:01:01.222
If you have any specific questions and want to reach out to him.

1069
01:01:01.582 --> 01:01:05.502
So this is a model in which

1070
01:01:05.542 --> 01:01:09.062
we have KRAS and LKB1, very similar to what I've been talking to you, but these

1071
01:01:09.102 --> 01:01:13.042
mice also have inducible expression of Cas9, and this

1072
01:01:13.122 --> 01:01:14.142
allows us to

1073
01:01:15.142 --> 01:01:19.122
both induce the tumors using a lentivirus cre, and also deliver a

1074
01:01:19.162 --> 01:01:23.042
guide RNA to the tumors such that the tumors that we turn on

1075
01:01:23.062 --> 01:01:26.922
the activating mutations, we can also manipulate different genes in those tumor

1076
01:01:27.002 --> 01:01:30.942
cells. And one of the genes that we first attempted to manipulate in

1077
01:01:30.982 --> 01:01:34.762
collaboration with Thalise's lab was PTGS2.

1078
01:01:35.122 --> 01:01:38.442
I'm sorry, PTGES, which is the last step in forming

1079
01:01:39.002 --> 01:01:40.162
prostaglandin E2.

1080
01:01:41.942 --> 01:01:45.802
And so when you do this, you can now see that PGE2 levels are

1081
01:01:45.862 --> 01:01:49.142
dramatically suppressed in the animals that receive the guide RNA versus animals

1082
01:01:49.162 --> 01:01:51.642
that don't receive a control guide RNA.

1083
01:01:52.762 --> 01:01:55.562
And then if you follow their body weight trajectories, you can see that the

1084
01:01:55.662 --> 01:01:57.362
knockdown of PTGES

1085
01:01:58.642 --> 01:02:02.242
prevents or delays the onset of cachexia quite significantly.

1086
01:02:05.282 --> 01:02:06.282
And in a separate model,

1087
01:02:07.122 --> 01:02:09.002
through another of our collaborators, Tony Hui,

1088
01:02:10.482 --> 01:02:13.882
we can perform a very similar cre CRISPR

1089
01:02:13.982 --> 01:02:17.862
mediated deletion of PTGS2, and this was done in

1090
01:02:17.882 --> 01:02:19.902
an allograft model in the C26 cells.

1091
01:02:21.162 --> 01:02:24.772
And you can see that this, in comparison to a non-cachectic C26,

1092
01:02:25.302 --> 01:02:29.282
the cachectic inducing C26 cell line leads to higher

1093
01:02:29.322 --> 01:02:31.042
amounts of PGE2 in the tumors,

1094
01:02:32.022 --> 01:02:34.752
and the CRISPR base knockout completely

1095
01:02:35.662 --> 01:02:37.362
reduces that amount of PGE2.

1096
01:02:39.542 --> 01:02:42.822
And then when you track their body weights over time, what you can see is that

1097
01:02:43.102 --> 01:02:46.862
the animals that have the PTGS2 knocked out are

1098
01:02:46.912 --> 01:02:50.842
protected from body weight loss in comparison to the cachectic C26

1099
01:02:50.882 --> 01:02:51.142
line.

1100
01:02:52.902 --> 01:02:55.002
So these data suggest that the PGE2

1101
01:02:56.021 --> 01:02:57.882
can be contributing to cachexia,

1102
01:02:58.762 --> 01:03:02.682
and work from Thalise's lab now in review, and work from Liberles's lab,

1103
01:03:03.722 --> 01:03:07.362
which was done in a setting of influenza, have very nicely shown that local

1104
01:03:07.402 --> 01:03:11.362
PGE2 can be detected by sensory neurons that then link

1105
01:03:11.442 --> 01:03:14.962
back to the brain in order to reduce appetite and contribute to wasting.

1106
01:03:15.022 --> 01:03:18.682
And this data's in review, but I think it'll be very convincing once it's out.

1107
01:03:21.882 --> 01:03:25.502
But we were wondering what could be the trigger for this PGE2

1108
01:03:25.542 --> 01:03:29.471
production, since these neutrophils are present and releasing

1109
01:03:29.502 --> 01:03:33.402
this prostaglandin. Is there an upstream trigger other than the tumor cells

1110
01:03:33.442 --> 01:03:35.052
themselves that can be leading to this?

1111
01:03:37.142 --> 01:03:40.642
And we started to think about what triggers this neutrophil

1112
01:03:41.262 --> 01:03:45.222
production, and one of the thoughts were that local bacteria could

1113
01:03:45.282 --> 01:03:48.702
